#FeministPartner @chellaman’s latest project, “Big Deaf” continues to push the boundaries of what it means to be accessible, inclusive, and equal in this world. ➡️ See more at @whatthefuckisthischella.

“Unfortunately the continuum of disability is rarely taught or acknowledged leaving stereotypes as the only outline non-disabled individuals have of disability. With 15% of the world’s population being disabled, the individuality of our community should come at no surprise…” 💭 @chellaman

In this project, @chellaman reflect’s on his own deaf identity to navigate the reality of the continuum of identity. You can discover the perpetual release of “Big Deaf”  at @whatthefuckisthischella ✨

“The Beauty Within” is a short film following sisters Aaraf (@aarafxadam) and Abrar Adam (@abrawrr) on their journey to find their individuality, voice, and strength. A film by @kanxsuda
✨ We interviewed Aaraf for film release, see link in bio. 🔗  These women embody the power of Black female heroism through their vulnerability and unity. The silent interaction between these sisters showcases the power and perseverance that lies within each of us— the beauty within. The film features ballerinas Sydnie Collins and Audrey Malek performing as guiding fairies, leading the main characters through their journey of self-identity. The audio throughout is a poem written to serve as a reminder that “ Black, Indigenous and women of color must always be present, visible and amplified.” - @aarafxadam

*Credits in the Comments*

TW: mention of suicide, if that's a difficult topic for you, please feel free to scroll past.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Resource created by @goodgoodgoodco in collaboration with @afspnational ➡️ “If you or someone you know is in danger and in need of immediate help, call the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline at 1-800-273-8255 or text TALK to 741741 to text with a trained Crisis Text Line crisis counselor.”
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
‍—
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
“Today is World Suicide Prevention Day. Suicide is a heavy topic, but the world would be a better place if we were all more equipped on how to talk about it. It's the perfect time to make sure you're prepared to help someone who shares with you that they have contemplated or are contemplating suicide.”
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
“If someone does share their suicidal thoughts with you, you may feel a lot of pressure to respond "correctly", but first and foremost remember: them sharing this with you is positive thing, and you now have the opportunity to help.”
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
“In collaboration with @afspnational, swipe to see some ways you can be there to support someone who's contemplating suicide” — visit @goodgoodgoodco link in our bio for more.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
#WSPD21 #SuicidePrevention #becomegoodnews

May be an image of text that says 'HOW το HELP SUPPORT SOMEONE CONTEMPLATING SUICIDE Encourage them to keep talking Keep the conversation going Let them know you want to hear more about how they're feeling, and what they going through. Express curiosity and interest in the details of what they're experiencing Ask about changes in their life, and how they re coping. "That situation sounds really difficult." "How did that make you feel when that happened?' "Have these thoughts led to any specific changes in your life, like trouble sleeping,or keeping up at work?" via AFSP'.

May be an image of text that says 'HOW TO HELP SUPPORT SOMEONE CONTEMPLATING SUICIDE How to respond if they are thinking about suicide If the person says they are contemplating suicide stay calm. Just because someoneis having thoughts of suicide, doesn't mean they're in immediate danger. Calmly listen to what they have to say, and ask some follow-up questions, like: "How often are you having these thoughts?" "When it gets really bad, what do you do?" "What scares you about these thoughts?" "What do you need to do to feel safe?" via AFSP'.

May be an image of text that says 'HOW το HELP SUPPORT SOMEONE CONTEMPLATING SUICIDE Help them connect with help When someone is already struggling, the idea of navigating insurance, finding a professional, or calling to make the appointment can seem especially challenging. Offer to help them take those steps however you feel comfortable. "I could call your insurance with you, or go online to find a mental health professional or substance use program. Or could sit with you while you do it. We can figure it out together." "I could drive or walk you to your appointment. Then we could have coffee afterwards." via AFSP'.

Ifthey ask you not to tell anyone, remind them how much you care for them and their safety, which may involve asking others for help. Tell them you want them to be involved in the conversation and that you'll be as discreet as possible. "Mental health treatment actually has even greater confidentiality safeguards than physical health treatment. via AFSP'.

👋 Hello @Feminist Community! We are taking part in today’s #WelcomeWednesday and re-introducing you to what it means when we say, ‘this community is rooted in intersectional feminism.’👇

We are working to provide a space for intersectional feminism that reflects our diversity. Our intersectional feminism is informed on frame works by Kimberlé Crenshaw and bell hooks.

There are many ways to be a feminist and we seek to uplift ‘feminism’ defined by bell hooks: 
“to be “feminist” in any authentic sense of the term is to want for all people, female and male, liberation from sexist role patterns, domination, and oppression.” (Ain't I a Woman: Black Women and Feminism by bell hooks) 
This is a community made up of a diverse global network of voices and creators. Before sharing we always ensure the message is aligned with our values and positively impactful through a lens of intersectionality, informed by Kimberlé Crenshaw:

‘honoring the multiple identities–race, sex, gender, class, disability, sexual orientations, ect.–in addition to the ways these identities relate to systems of privilege and oppression’  (Demarginalizing the Intersection of Race and Sex, Kimberlé Crenshaw 1989).

We are the messengers. We amplify the work and stories of feminist creators across Instagram.

While we amplify these voices we rely on our community to 🤳 share, follow, and support the creators’ represented on this page. 💞

Thank you for being a part of our community! ➡️ Swipe for feminist reading recommendations to learn more! #FeministForAll

What is your advice to young and aspiring photographers and environmental activists?
“Everything is possible, never think you can’t do or achieve. Follow your gut and your opinion, your style develops your own signature because that is what makes you unique.” @thirzaschaap

node.text:
Until the summer of 1989, largely, the voices of Black women had been left out of the mainstream conversation around abortion access. That year, 16 Black women made #Herstory by publishing the first collective statement advocating for equal access to abortion, “We Remember: African-American Women are for Reproductive Freedom.” U.S. Rep. Shirley Chisholm, U.S. Rep. Maxine Waters & civil rights activist Dorothy Height were among the notable names who signed the unprecedented brochure. 31 years later the fight for reproductive freedom persists.

Source: “Black women and the fight for abortion rights: How this brochure sparked the movement for reproductive freedom” by Natelegé Whaley for @nbcnews
Visit our link in bio to read the full article. ​

Byllye Avery, founder of Black Women’s Health Imperative, suggested the group write the pamphlet, the most common form of distributing new ideas in the public forum in the era before political hashtags. The pamphlet would act as a permission slip to speak out about abortion access. “Now once again somebody is trying to say that we can’t handle the freedom of choice,” the document said. “Only this time they’re saying African-American women can’t think for themselves and, therefore, can’t be allowed to make serious decisions. Somebody’s saying that we should not have the freedom to take charge of our personal lives and protect our health, that we only have limited rights over our bodies.”

Planned Parenthood sponsored production of the 250,000 “We Remember” pamphlets and were first distributed, at anti-apartheid demonstrations, anti-r*pe rallies and other public venues. 

In commemorating this public statement, there are some parallels to the state of abortion access in today’s America. Reproductive health advocates say Roe v. Wade could be overturned which could have devastating effects for low-income women of color.   As of 2014, Black women are 28% of those who sought abortions, compared to 36% of white women and 25% of Hispanic women. Meanwhile, 60% of Black American adults say abortions should be legal in all or most cases, according to a Pew Center Research report in 2018.

#ProtectAbortionAccess #BansOffOurBodies
